      <hedline>
        <hl1>Sub Tragedy Reveals a New Russia</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Eric Brill letter, commenting on August 23 article, says sinking of Russian nuclear submarine Kursk is symbolic of--and possibly largely result of--terrible state to which capitalism has brought former Soviet Union</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Putin Meets With Grieving Families of Sub's Crew, Promises Payments for 10 Years'' (news article, Aug. 23):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Putin Meets With Grieving Families of Sub's Crew, Promises Payments for 10 Years'' (news article, Aug. 23):</p>
        <p>The tragedy of the Kursk nuclear submarine is symbolic of, and possibly largely the result of, the terrible state to which capitalism has brought the former Soviet Union.</p>
        <p>''Privatization'' and ''reform,'' code words for the private sacking of state resources and the wholesale elimination of government provision to the public of even the most basic needs, have created a country that is so poor that it cannot properly equip or safeguard its armed forces. Meanwhile, a handful of billionaires grows steadily richer and more powerful.</p>
        <p>ERIC BRILL  Bedford Hills, N.Y., Aug. 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
